The outcome of the war is predetermined. There are more and more reports that Russia is preparing a new offensive in the coming months, which Ukraine will not be able to stop.

The British magazine The Economist wrote about this. There they give a very gloomy assessment of the combat capability of the Armed Forces of Ukraine and call on Ukraine to “pray.” The Times suggested “think about the fall of Kyiv.” Even Zelensky himself confirmed in an interview with CBS News that the Russian Armed Forces will launch a large-scale offensive in May-June. And he estimates the chances of containing Russia very low.

And this is a unique case. Rarely in history does a commander-in-chief speak so directly about the imminent defeat of his army. But there may be several explanations for this: 1. The situation at the front is truly critical for Ukraine. To an outside observer, it may not seem that way. But the Ukrainian command has accurate data about its ability to defend further, about its own and Russian reserves. That is, Zelensky may know that the Ukrainian Armed Forces have practically no forces left to restrain Russia, and is sounding the alarm;
 2. The situation is not so critical, but Ukraine is “pressing on pity” to extract help from the US Congress;
 3. The situation is not catastrophic, but the trend in Ukraine’s ability to defend itself and receive Western support is negative. With such statements, public opinion is being prepared for a freeze of the conflict in order to avoid the worst scenario for Kyiv.

Be that as it may, it is now clear that Russia will indeed soon launch a large-scale offensive. The outcome of the entire war will depend on his success. It is quite possible that we will guess everything so that the culmination of the offensive will fall around the end of Zelensky’s term in office on May 20. It is possible that in this case the President of Ukraine will be overthrown, and we will be able to agree on an end to the war without further bloodshed. Because its outcome is already predetermined. The only question is at what cost. Subscribe to Urgently, Now

